{{For|the novel by Jake Arnott|The Long Firm}}
A '''long firm fraud''' (also known as a ''consumer credit fraud'')<ref>{{cite web|title=ACPOS Best Practice Guide to Long Firm Fraud|url=http://www.eastscotlandfraudforum.org.uk/long-firm-fraud.asp|website=East of Scotland Fraud Forum|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819195315/http://www.eastscotlandfraudforum.org.uk/long-firm-fraud.asp|archivedate=August 19, 2008}}</ref> is a fraud that uses a trading company set up for [[fraud]]ulent purposes; the basic operation is to run the company as an apparently legitimate business by buying goods and paying suppliers promptly to secure a good [[credit (finance)|credit]] record.<ref>“The Profession of Violence: the rise and fall of the Kray twins”- Pearson, J  London, [[Weidenfeld and Nicolson]], 1972ISBN 0297995847</ref> Once they are sufficiently well-established, the perpetrators then purchase the next round of goods on credit and decamp with both the goods and profits from previous sales. The goods can then be sold elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.actionfraud.org.uk/fraud_protection/long_term_and_short_term_fraud |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210111202/http://www.actionfraud.org.uk/fraud_protection/long_term_and_short_term_fraud |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2010-02-10 |title=Long Term and Short Term Fraud |publisher=actionfraud |date= |accessdate=2012-02-14 |df= }}</ref> The procedure needs a certain amount of money to set up, often the proceeds from another crime or a previous long firm. Sometimes the individual who does jail time for assisting with the fraud is paid for their time served.

Long firm frauds have become significantly less common in recent years since it is no longer possible to operate for any length of time without leaving a significant [[wikt:paper trail|paper trail]].

