{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Use British English|date=November 2013}} '''[[Queen (band)|Queen]] live in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] 1976''' was a famous concert by the band. The concert took place on 18 September, during the hot summer of 1976. It was part of a brief summer tour of the UK by the band; they also played in [[Edinburgh]] and [[Cardiff]] on this tour.
The Hyde Park gig was a free concert, which drew in a crowd of over 150,000, which was one of the largest audiences for any concert in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=Queen: Full Biography |publisher=MTV.com |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418041047/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/queen/artist.jhtml |accessdate=2009-04-09 |quote=In the summer of 1976, they performed a free concert at London's Hyde Park that broke attendance records...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=2005-03-30 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131014961.html |title=Win Tickets To See Queen & Paul Rodgers; Concert Week In The Evening Standard.}}</ref> The free concert was organised by [[Richard Branson]], an entrepreneur at the time.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[BBC]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/stadium-rock/queen-play-hyde-park/ |title=Queen play Hyde Park |accessdate=2009-04-09}}</ref>
There is more than one audio source of this concert as well as a video. According to [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], the drummer of Queen, the complete show was supposed to be shown on TV in early 1977 but was never aired. Since then, the footage has leaked out to collectors, though in terrible quality. Over the years, some of the footage has been shown in various documentaries and there are rumors of a future official release. The 2011 reissue of ''[[A Day at the Races (album)|A Day at the Races]]'' includes a performance of "You Take My Breath Away" from this date.
The rest of the day's music was provided by The Kiki Dee Band, Supercharge, The Rich Kids (not to be confused with Midge Ure's band of the same name), Broken Wreck Chords and Steve Hillage. Elton John did not appear duetting with Kiki Dee for "Don't go breaking my heart". She sang to a 2/3 life-sized cardboard cut-out of Elton instead.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.virgin.com/richard-branson/promoting-queen-and-jamming-roger-taylor |title= Promoting Queen and jamming with Roger Taylor |last=Branson |first=Richard |authorlink= Richard Branson |date=26 August 2016 |website=Virgin.com |publisher= Virgin Records official blog |access-date=26 July 2018 |quote="Beforehand, I remember Kiki Dee singing Don’t Go Breaking My Heart to a cardboard cut-out of Elton John, who couldn’t make it."}}</ref>
